The CSS file begins with a comment block that describes the purpose of the stylesheet. Comments in CSS are written between /* and */ and are ignored by the browser. In this case, the comment explains that the file is called “Style.css” and that it includes comprehensive styling such as a three-column layout, a color scheme, responsive design, typography, and accessibility features.

The next line uses the @import rule to load external fonts from Google Fonts. Specifically, it imports the font families “Garamond” and “Inter.” The Inter font is loaded with two font weights: 400 (regular) and 700 (bold). The parameter display=swap ensures that text remains visible while the custom fonts are loading. This improves performance and user experience.

The stylesheet then defines styles for the body element. The font-family property sets the default font of the entire page to “Inter,” with a generic sans-serif font as a fallback. The background-color is set to a light gray tone (#f5f5f5), which creates a soft, neutral background. The margin: 0; removes the browser’s default outer spacing around the page, ensuring that the layout starts at the very edge of the viewport. The padding: 20px; adds space inside the body element, creating consistent spacing between the content and the edges of the screen.

Next, typography for headings is defined. The rule targets all <h1>, <h2>, and <h3> elements. Their font family is set to “Garamond,” with a generic serif font as a fallback. This creates visual contrast between headings (serif) and body text (sans-serif). The text color is set to #333, which is a dark gray. This slightly softer tone improves readability compared to pure black.

The stylesheet then defines a three-column layout using Flexbox. The .container class is set to display: flex;, which activates the Flexbox layout system. The property justify-content: space-between; distributes the columns evenly with space between them. The flex-wrap: wrap; property allows columns to move onto a new line if there is not enough horizontal space. The margin: 0 -10px; offsets the internal padding of the columns so that the layout remains aligned.

The .column class defines the styling for individual columns within the container. The property flex: 1; ensures that each column grows and shrinks equally, distributing available space evenly. The padding: 10px; adds space inside each column so that content does not touch the edges. The min-width: 250px; ensures that columns never become narrower than 250 pixels, which helps maintain readability even when the screen size changes.

Responsive design is implemented using a media query. The rule @media (max-width: 768px) applies styles only when the screen width is 768 pixels or less, which typically corresponds to tablets or smartphones. Inside this media query, the .container changes its flex-direction to column. This stacks the columns vertically instead of horizontally, making the layout more suitable for smaller screens and improving usability on mobile devices.

The stylesheet also includes accessibility features for buttons and links. The rule targeting button and a elements sets cursor: pointer;, which changes the mouse cursor to a hand icon to indicate interactivity. The background color is set to a bright blue (#007bff), and the text color is set to white to create strong contrast. Padding is added to increase the clickable area, improving usability. The default border is removed with border: none;, and border-radius: 5px; rounds the corners slightly for a modern appearance. The text-align: center; centers the text within the element, and text-decoration: none; removes the underline from links so they visually resemble buttons.

Focus styles are defined using the :focus pseudo-class. When a button or link receives keyboard focus (for example, through the Tab key), it displays a yellow outline (2px solid #ffcc00). This visual indicator is important for accessibility because it helps keyboard users see which element is currently active.

Hover styles are defined using the :hover pseudo-class. When the user moves the mouse pointer over a button or link, the background color changes to a darker blue (#0056b3). This provides visual feedback that the element is interactive.

Finally, a comment mentions WCAG AA compliance. WCAG stands for Web Content Accessibility Guidelines. The comment indicates that the chosen color combinations are intended to provide sufficient contrast between text and background colors, improving readability and ensuring better accessibility for users with visual impairments.
